Oh, that would be Uncle Paul.
They call him that.

262
00:19:21,500 --> 00:19:22,749
Don't you know him?

263
00:19:22,833 --> 00:19:24,082
He's a mate of Sean's.

264
00:19:24,167 --> 00:19:25,791
Well, that's his problem, isn't it?

265
00:19:27,292 --> 00:19:29,791
I think I'll make a cuppa tea.
Don't want to eat nothing.

266
00:19:29,875 --> 00:19:31,291
One too many last night?

267
00:19:31,583 --> 00:19:33,249
We went to this club up in town.

268
00:19:33,333 --> 00:19:35,082
You know, Cigale?

269
00:19:35,167 --> 00:19:36,207
I see.

270
00:19:36,292 --> 00:19:38,499
Steve looked a bit sweaty
when the bill came.

271
00:19:38,583 --> 00:19:41,499
Said he'd stay down on Union Street
with his mates next time.

272
00:19:41,583 --> 00:19:43,707
Well, won't have no choice tonight.

273
00:19:43,792 --> 00:19:45,499
Patrols don't let you out.

274
00:19:47,792 --> 00:19:49,832
I wanted to go to this party.

275
00:19:49,958 --> 00:19:51,541
Girl I knew at school.

276
00:19:51,625 --> 00:19:53,249
Her dad's loaded.

277
00:19:53,375 --> 00:19:55,041
Should be posh, you know?

278
00:19:55,458 --> 00:19:57,541
You might be alright
just the two of you.

279
00:19:57,708 --> 00:19:59,082
Go in a cab.

280
00:19:59,250 --> 00:20:01,499
SUE: Malcolm getting
an early train is he, Gail?

281
00:20:01,625 --> 00:20:02,832
I hope so.

282
00:20:04,208 --> 00:20:06,624
I rang him last night.
He sounded really fed up.

283
00:20:06,792 --> 00:20:08,499
He always does
when he goes home.

284
00:20:09,083 --> 00:20:10,707
Why did he go then?

285
00:20:11,042 --> 00:20:12,666
I don't know.
His brother's on leave.

286
00:20:13,417 --> 00:20:14,999
They're quite close, aren't they?

287
00:20:15,083 --> 00:20:17,082
At least, he's supposed
to be on leave anyway.

288
00:20:17,375 --> 00:20:19,166
I don't know.
You know what he's like.

289
00:20:19,250 --> 00:20:21,332
He's a bit of a one for stories.

290
00:20:21,458 --> 00:20:23,541
I'll sort him out, you'll see.

291
00:20:23,792 --> 00:20:26,666
(INDISTINCT TRAIN ANNOUNCEMENT)

292
00:20:31,542 --> 00:20:34,332
(DISTANT MUSIC PLAYS)

293
00:20:56,750 --> 00:20:57,707
Gail?

294
00:20:58,042 --> 00:20:59,332
It's Malcolm.

295
00:20:59,500 --> 00:21:02,582
Look, I'm on the... the 9:50, OK?

296
00:21:03,458 --> 00:21:05,374
No, he didn't show up.

297
00:21:06,167 --> 00:21:08,416
(MACHINES BEEP)

298
00:23:05,083 --> 00:23:06,707
MALCOLM:
Yeah, I can't talk now.

299
00:23:07,042 --> 00:23:08,207
See ya, OK?

300
00:23:16,375 --> 00:23:18,874
Listen, I'll tell you something
about that area.

301
00:23:18,958 --> 00:23:21,707
It's Irish, mate.
That's what it is around there.

302
00:23:21,792 --> 00:23:23,416
Don't start going on
about the Irish.

303
00:23:24,042 --> 00:23:26,166
CHRIS:
IRA. Know what I mean?

304
00:23:26,833 --> 00:23:29,416
You don't want to go down there, mate.
If you have to have one

305
00:23:29,500 --> 00:23:31,207
order your Stag by phone.

306
00:23:31,292 --> 00:23:32,624
You daft prat.

307
00:23:32,708 --> 00:23:35,999
Go down there with a haircut like that,
you'll lose your fucking knees.

308
00:23:36,375 --> 00:23:37,874
It's not a joke, Chris.

309
00:23:37,958 --> 00:23:39,499
Mal, old son!
John, this is Malcolm.

310
00:23:39,583 --> 00:23:41,791
Malcolm, this is John. John, this is Malcolm.
Malcolm, this is John.

311
00:23:41,875 --> 00:23:44,207
- Oh, shut up.
- It's not a joke.

312
00:23:44,333 --> 00:23:46,457
A Triumph Stag is, old son.

313
00:23:46,542 --> 00:23:48,082
The IRA.

314
00:23:48,958 --> 00:23:50,624
Well, you know what they say, Mal?

315
00:23:51,625 --> 00:23:53,291
Three's a crowd.

316
00:24:02,667 --> 00:24:04,291
You don't look well, Mark.

