00:24:05,125 --> 00:24:06,707
Got a hangover, Mum.

318
00:24:07,208 --> 00:24:08,499
Typical.

319
00:24:08,875 --> 00:24:10,541
You can shut up for a start.

320
00:24:10,875 --> 00:24:12,457
Watch your manners.

321
00:24:16,333 --> 00:24:17,541
ls that a wig?

322
00:24:18,583 --> 00:24:19,791
Course not.

323
00:24:20,833 --> 00:24:22,041
Stupid.

324
00:24:24,583 --> 00:24:26,249
Don't you get in trouble at school?

325
00:24:27,500 --> 00:24:29,916
Vegetable dye, innit?
Washes out.

326
00:24:30,583 --> 00:24:31,999
Am I going right?

327
00:24:32,708 --> 00:24:35,207
Yeah, it's just down the end
of this road, on the left.

328
00:24:35,292 --> 00:24:36,416
Number eight.

329
00:24:48,042 --> 00:24:49,166
- OK?
- Yeah.

330
00:24:50,250 --> 00:24:51,374
You look rough.

331
00:24:54,292 --> 00:24:55,791
They're all sitting in the car.

332
00:24:55,875 --> 00:24:57,832
Yeah, OK. Won't be a sec.

333
00:25:02,458 --> 00:25:03,624
Your sister coming?

334
00:25:03,708 --> 00:25:04,624
Yeah.

335
00:25:06,167 --> 00:25:07,541
You don't have to come.

336
00:25:08,667 --> 00:25:09,666
VINCENT:
What?

337
00:25:11,083 --> 00:25:13,041
You can change your mind
about coming.

338
00:25:13,542 --> 00:25:14,707
I want to come.

339
00:25:16,375 --> 00:25:17,874
Gill 16 yet?

340
00:25:18,667 --> 00:25:19,916
Piss off.

341
00:25:22,583 --> 00:25:24,332
Your mum and dad coming?

342
00:25:24,875 --> 00:25:26,166
Going shopping.

343
00:25:27,250 --> 00:25:28,374
Even better.

344
00:25:28,917 --> 00:25:30,124
(HE CHUCKLES)

345
00:25:33,250 --> 00:25:34,249
Refreshments.

346
00:25:48,542 --> 00:25:50,249
MARK'S FATHER:
Come on! We've been waiting.

347
00:25:50,333 --> 00:25:52,332
Wouldn’t stand for you
if you were my old man.

348
00:25:52,417 --> 00:25:53,874
Bad-tempered old sod.

349
00:25:58,583 --> 00:26:01,041
- (SHIP HORN BLARES)
- (GULLS SQUAWK)

350
00:26:27,375 --> 00:26:31,041
Come staggering out the main gates
this morning feeling really putrid

351
00:26:31,208 --> 00:26:33,207
and there he was,
camera at the ready.

352
00:26:34,125 --> 00:26:35,582
Yeah, it looks a nice one.

353
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:37,374
Yeah, he's just bought it.

354
00:26:37,500 --> 00:26:38,916
Pride and joy.

355
00:26:39,500 --> 00:26:41,457
I'm gonna get one in the States, cheaper.

356
00:26:41,542 --> 00:26:43,082
Bloke I know got one last trip.

357
00:26:43,167 --> 00:26:45,041
Real beauty, it were,
electronic and all.

358
00:26:46,375 --> 00:26:47,457
Here.

359
00:26:47,917 --> 00:26:49,749
Best thing for a hangover
is a bit more.

360
00:26:51,375 --> 00:26:53,457
TOUR GUIDE ON PA: Good afternoon,
ladies and gentlemen.

361
00:26:53,542 --> 00:26:55,916
Welcome aboard the Plymouth Bell.

362
00:26:56,000 --> 00:26:58,666
- We'll do our best to...
- I got on with Dave's crowd.

363
00:26:58,875 --> 00:27:00,332
More fool you, mate.

364
00:27:02,167 --> 00:27:03,749
I got through 30 quid.

365
00:27:03,833 --> 00:27:05,041
30 quid!

366
00:27:06,125 --> 00:27:07,666
Anyway, where'd you get to?
I didn't see you.

367
00:27:07,750 --> 00:27:08,791
White Swan.

368
00:27:08,875 --> 00:27:10,832
- It's boring.
- Get stuffed.

369
00:27:11,833 --> 00:27:15,332
TOUR GUIDE ON PA: The lighthouse
is the old Eddystone lighthouse.

370
00:27:16,667 --> 00:27:19,874
The monument with the green ball on top

371
00:27:20,125 --> 00:27:24,291
is the naval war memorial
for the two World Wars.

372
00:27:24,375 --> 00:27:26,041
I've been up since 7:00.

373
00:27:26,667 --> 00:27:28,332
These people come and woke me up...

374
00:27:28,833 --> 00:27:30,499
started firing questions at me.

375
00:27:31,208 --> 00:27:33,332
What have you been up to,
young Mark, eh?

376
00:27:33,583 --> 00:27:35,499
- There was trouble last night.
- Oh yeah?

377
00:27:36,917 --> 00:27:39,291
I met this bloke, a young kid.

378
00:27:40,042 --> 00:27:41,166
What, old as you, were he?

379
00:27:41,542 --> 00:27:43,707
Oh look, Vincent, just listen, will you?

380
00:27:45,500 --> 00:27:46,791
I met this kid.

381
00:27:47,625 --> 00:27:50,041
Pissed out of his head he was,
all on his tod.

382
00:27:51,000 --> 00:27:52,416
Well, he got slung out.

383
00:27:53,250 --> 00:27:55,416
That big bouncer, Frank,
he took him out.

384
00:27:55,500 --> 00:27:56,666
Oh, he's the worst.

385
00:27:56,750 --> 00:27:58,207
MARK:
They thought it was a fight.

386
00:27:58,750 --> 00:28:00,457
Put 'em right on that anyway.

387
00:28:00,792 --> 00:28:03,624
Doesn't sounds as if you were in a state
to know what the fuck went on.

388
00:28:04,625 --> 00:28:05,916
(HE SIGHS)

389
00:28:06,250 --> 00:28:08,041
Well, he couldn't fight anyone.

390
00:28:08,167 --> 00:28:09,541
He was legless.

391
00:28:09,917 --> 00:28:11,374
Except when he was dancing.

392
00:28:11,958 --> 00:28:13,457
You've been dreaming, mate.

393
00:28:14,750 --> 00:28:16,249
They don't know who he is.

394
00:28:17,042 --> 00:28:18,374
Nothing on him.

395
00:28:20,625 --> 00:28:22,291
He's still unconscious, see?

396
00:28:23,083 --> 00:28:24,332
Head injuries.

397
00:28:25,625 --> 00:28:28,041
Yeah, well, you can't do nothing.
Just keep out of it.

398
00:28:28,292 --> 00:28:30,832
TOUR GUIDE ON PA:
It fires the Exocet missile.

399
00:28:30,958 --> 00:28:32,666
It carries a helicopter.

400
00:28:33,042 --> 00:28:35,707
It's a very fast ship,
which is powered

401
00:28:35,792 --> 00:28:38,374
by Olympus Rolls Royce engines

402
00:28:38,958 --> 00:28:40,707
which are gas turbines.

403
00:28:41,333 --> 00:28:43,749
It gives this ship or this class of ship

404
00:28:43,875 --> 00:28:47,207
a speed of around 34 knots.

405
00:28:48,042 --> 00:28:50,207
This trip's for your benefit, not mine.

406
00:28:50,375 --> 00:28:51,624
I weren't asked.

407
00:28:51,708 --> 00:28:53,999
I can think of better things to do
on my last day ashore

408
00:28:54,083 --> 00:28:55,541
than look at bloody ships.

409
00:28:55,625 --> 00:28:57,249
I'm cold.

410
00:29:01,292 --> 00:29:02,499
Christ.

411
00:29:02,750 --> 00:29:03,874
It's the age.

412
00:29:03,958 --> 00:29:04,874
ls it?

413
00:29:05,208 --> 00:29:07,957
My sister was like that, her age,
when she were older than me.

414
00:29:08,208 --> 00:29:10,082
Nearly drove me fucking mad.

415
00:29:10,833 --> 00:29:12,291
She get better, did she?

416
00:29:12,917 --> 00:29:14,457
Don't know.
Don't see her no more.

417
00:29:15,875 --> 00:29:18,874
TOUR GUIDE ON PA:
This ship was built here, at Plymouth.

418
00:29:19,292 --> 00:29:20,999
It carries a helicopter.

419
00:29:21,542 --> 00:29:25,207
You see the missile platform
on the bows of the ship quite clearly.

420
00:29:25,583 --> 00:29:27,249
I've been looking forward to this trip.

421
00:29:27,333 --> 00:29:28,541
You always do.

422
00:29:29,083 --> 00:29:30,957
Got nothing to stay home for, have I?

423
00:29:33,708 --> 00:29:34,874
West Coast, eh?

424
00:29:34,958 --> 00:29:36,207
California.

425
00:29:36,958 --> 00:29:38,374
California!

426
00:29:39,167 --> 00:29:42,999
TOUR GUIDE ON PA: This is the new
nuclear refitting yard here at Devonport.

427
00:29:43,708 --> 00:29:45,666
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

428
00:29:53,875 --> 00:29:54,832
Alright?

429
00:29:55,458 --> 00:29:56,582
Better?

430
00:29:56,667 --> 00:29:57,832
Better keep off the tea.

431
00:29:57,917 --> 00:29:59,416
(THEY CHUCKLE)

432
00:30:00,833 --> 00:30:02,707
Well, it's quicker here to Plymouth.

433
00:30:02,792 --> 00:30:05,416
I still don't quite believe
this is all happening.

434
00:30:05,500 --> 00:30:09,332
Ah, well,
we can't be lucky every time.

435
00:30:10,792 --> 00:30:14,332
You try doing an exchange when you want
to be away for a few months.

436
00:30:14,417 --> 00:30:15,707
It's a doddle.

437
00:30:15,958 --> 00:30:18,541
There's blokes queueing up to stop you
for your shore posting.

438
00:30:21,042 --> 00:30:23,166
It's harder this way 'round, love.

439
00:30:25,583 --> 00:30:27,791
Oh, it'll be alright.

440
00:30:58,250 --> 00:31:00,041
You're never gonna wear them,
are you?

441
00:31:00,667 --> 00:31:01,957
Of course I am.

442
00:31:02,625 --> 00:31:05,291
The sun shines
all the time on the West Coast.

443
00:31:06,500 --> 00:31:08,749
Beach Boys, all that stuff.

444
00:31:09,500 --> 00:31:11,207
You look like a bloody poof.

445
00:31:12,167 --> 00:31:13,416
Laid back.

446
00:31:14,167 --> 00:31:16,374
That's what these are, my son.

447
00:31:16,708 --> 00:31:17,874
Laid back.

448
00:31:18,167 --> 00:31:19,707
(HE LAUGHS)

449
00:31:19,875 --> 00:31:22,332
Drink up, young Malcolm White.
Your round next.

450
00:31:22,417 --> 00:31:23,707
Oh, I'm taking it easy.

451
00:31:25,292 --> 00:31:27,291
Fucking skinful last night.

452
00:31:27,458 --> 00:31:31,332
Not matching vodkas with that mum of yours?
You naughty fellow.

453
00:31:31,958 --> 00:31:34,207
(POP MUSIC PLAYS)

454
00:31:35,708 --> 00:31:36,957
Who's winning?

455
00:31:37,958 --> 00:31:40,374
- It's a bit hard to say.
- At the moment.

456
00:31:42,458 --> 00:31:44,041
You going past to Plymouth?

457
00:31:44,542 --> 00:31:46,749
- Penzance.
- MALCOLM: That's nice.

458
00:31:48,750 --> 00:31:49,749
You sisters?

459
00:31:50,625 --> 00:31:51,666
No.

460
00:31:52,458 --> 00:31:54,916
MALCOLM:
I like Cornwall. It's nice there.

461
00:31:56,417 --> 00:31:58,457
When were you in Cornwall then?

462
00:31:59,333 --> 00:32:00,374
Holidays.

463
00:32:00,833 --> 00:32:01,791
Yeah.

464
00:32:02,083 --> 00:32:04,666
I went there every summer
as a kid. It's really good.

465
00:32:05,208 --> 00:32:06,707
Whereabouts did you stay?

466
00:32:08,375 --> 00:32:10,332
Uh... it's, um...

467
00:32:10,750 --> 00:32:12,874
Well, it's a little place near... St. Ives.

468
00:32:14,000 --> 00:32:16,124
Nice, uh, cottage was it, eh?

469
00:32:16,875 --> 00:32:19,832
Wake in the morning
to the cry of the gulls?

470
00:32:21,917 --> 00:32:23,166
(HE LAUGHS)

471
00:32:23,833 --> 00:32:24,707
In college?

472
00:32:25,500 --> 00:32:26,832
Yes, that's right.

473
00:32:29,083 --> 00:32:30,749
MALCOLM:
I bet you're older than me.

474
00:32:33,875 --> 00:32:36,332
I've been in the navy
since I was at school.

475
00:32:39,083 --> 00:32:40,832
I'd say they were younger.

476
00:32:41,375 --> 00:32:42,541
It's your round.

477
00:32:42,958 --> 00:32:44,916
(HE LAUGHS)

478
00:33:25,292 --> 00:33:26,874
You alright, Steve, our son?

479
00:33:26,958 --> 00:33:28,166
Yeah, of course.

480
00:33:28,250 --> 00:33:29,374
You're doing well.

481
00:33:30,875 --> 00:33:31,791
(HE SIGHS)

482
00:33:31,875 --> 00:33:34,291
I was having a drink
with Sean McKay last night.

483
00:33:34,667 --> 00:33:36,082
- Oh yeah?
- Mm.

484
00:33:36,625 --> 00:33:37,916
He's a bit upset.

485
00:33:40,333 --> 00:33:43,207
Well, he's very upset
about you and that bird of his.

486
00:33:43,542 --> 00:33:44,874
Sue, is it?

487
00:33:47,625 --> 00:33:49,874
Look, I'd leave it out if I was you.

488
00:33:50,417 --> 00:33:52,332
Well, last night ashore and all.

489
00:33:52,500 --> 00:33:55,082
Look, it's all finished
between her and McKay.

490
00:33:55,167 --> 00:33:56,082
She told me.

491
00:33:56,167 --> 00:33:59,207
Well, if he sees you down Union Street
with her tonight, he'll have you.

492
00:33:59,292 --> 00:34:00,582
He's a fucking nutter.

493
00:34:01,042 --> 00:34:02,582
He can be a bit nasty.

494
00:34:05,292 --> 00:34:09,207
OK... it's just you're gonna be on ship
with him come tomorrow

495
00:34:09,292 --> 00:34:10,832
whether you like it or not.

496
00:34:10,917 --> 00:34:12,041
So what?

497
00:34:12,167 --> 00:34:13,916
He can't do nothing there, can he?

498
00:34:16,250 --> 00:34:17,249
Come on.

499
00:34:17,583 --> 00:34:18,499
Right.

500
00:34:18,583 --> 00:34:19,749
Let's get on with it.

501
00:34:19,833 --> 00:34:21,457
- Yeah.
- Right.

502
00:34:23,208 --> 00:34:25,916
(GULLS SQUAWK)

503
00:34:32,292 --> 00:34:34,874
MARIE: If you're waiting
for the Spanish Armada

504
00:34:35,792 --> 00:34:37,082
you've missed it.

505
00:34:38,583 --> 00:34:40,791
Look, we come into town
for a night out.

506
00:34:40,875 --> 00:34:42,874
We spent five minutes in my club.

507
00:34:43,708 --> 00:34:45,416
Why am I a fucking villain?

508
00:34:45,667 --> 00:34:47,624
It was him who threw up
all over you, wasn't it?

509
00:34:49,042 --> 00:34:50,166
Yes, Stan.

510
00:34:50,792 --> 00:34:51,791
Wasn't it?

511
00:34:51,958 --> 00:34:54,832
That doesn't mean he deserves
to end up in hospital.

512
00:34:55,292 --> 00:34:56,874
I'm sorry about the boy.

513
00:34:56,958 --> 00:34:58,166
Really, I am.

514
00:34:58,542 --> 00:35:00,207
That's not good enough, Stan.

515
00:35:01,125 --> 00:35:03,457
I mean, they're all still there,
aren't they?

516
00:35:03,750 --> 00:35:05,791
Frank and his like,
your employees?

517
00:35:06,750 --> 00:35:09,749
They're all still there,
getting ready for another night

518
00:35:09,833 --> 00:35:12,291
and I suppose the hospital's getting ready
for another night too.

519
00:35:12,542 --> 00:35:15,832
Marie, love,
both sides get hurt in a war.

520
00:35:16,542 --> 00:35:19,291
Oh, yes, right.

521
