- Yeah.

782
00:49:38,625 --> 00:49:40,957
- Would you sign that for me, please?
- Yeah, sure.

783
00:49:47,208 --> 00:49:49,082
Thank you. That's room 108.

784
00:49:49,167 --> 00:49:51,041
- First floor.
- Ah, lovely, ta.

785
00:49:57,292 --> 00:49:59,499
- (PHONE RINGS)
- (HE CHUCKLES)

786
00:50:02,375 --> 00:50:03,874
- It's here, eh?
- Yeah.

787
00:50:03,958 --> 00:50:05,041
Shall I go on in?

788
00:50:16,375 --> 00:50:18,874
(WATER RUNS)

789
00:50:26,333 --> 00:50:27,582
OK, love?

790
00:50:28,167 --> 00:50:29,874
Bit of a backache.

791
00:50:39,250 --> 00:50:40,666
There's not much time.

792
00:50:41,500 --> 00:50:42,916
Don't keep saying that.

793
00:50:46,958 --> 00:50:48,249
You glad I come?

794
00:50:49,167 --> 00:50:50,332
Yeah.

795
00:50:50,417 --> 00:50:52,207
It's gonna be ever so dull.

796
00:50:53,083 --> 00:50:55,666
Plenty of other chances
to go on the piss, stateside.

797
00:50:55,750 --> 00:50:57,541
Oh, got it all worked out then?

798
00:50:57,625 --> 00:50:58,999
(HE CHUCKLES)

799
00:50:59,458 --> 00:51:00,541
Tonight...

800
00:51:02,125 --> 00:51:03,582
just be the two of us.

801
00:51:09,292 --> 00:51:10,457
(DISTANT RATTLING)

802
00:51:15,958 --> 00:51:17,166
Nice view.

803
00:51:18,083 --> 00:51:19,124
Hmm?

804
00:51:20,917 --> 00:51:22,166
The kitchens.

805
00:51:41,708 --> 00:51:43,124
(CAR HORN TOOTS)

806
00:51:46,375 --> 00:51:49,249
(TRAIN HORN BLARES)

807
00:51:57,333 --> 00:51:59,749
I enjoyed the evening otherwise.

808
00:52:00,500 --> 00:52:01,874
So did I, love.

809
00:52:02,583 --> 00:52:07,041
It's always a treat,
night out in a hotel and everything.

810
00:52:07,458 --> 00:52:08,499
ls it?

811
00:52:09,208 --> 00:52:10,416
Yes, really.

812
00:52:11,958 --> 00:52:14,582
Haven't forgotten, you know,
the life I had before.

813
00:52:16,833 --> 00:52:18,207
Said goodbye to Vincent?

814
00:52:19,833 --> 00:52:20,916
It's funny.

815
00:52:22,042 --> 00:52:23,874
We're that much apart.

816
00:52:27,083 --> 00:52:31,291
Whether he's here in Plymouth
or someplace on the other side of the world

817
00:52:31,958 --> 00:52:34,707
it doesn't seem to make us
less apart or more apart.

818
00:52:34,792 --> 00:52:36,291
We're just the same.

819
00:52:37,833 --> 00:52:39,332
Occasional letter.

820
00:52:40,333 --> 00:52:43,457
Occasional phone call
from the phone box in Plymouth

821
00:52:43,542 --> 00:52:45,082
or one in Hong Kong.

822
00:52:48,292 --> 00:52:49,957
You're talking rubbish, Marie, love.

823
00:52:52,708 --> 00:52:55,749
Can I send you some money
to buy something in America?

824
00:53:06,792 --> 00:53:07,791
Tea?

825
00:53:08,125 --> 00:53:09,749
Oh, thanks, son.

826
00:53:14,917 --> 00:53:16,916
(MUSIC PLAYS ON RADIO)

827
00:53:17,000 --> 00:53:18,249
- Tea?
- Ta.

828
00:53:28,375 --> 00:53:31,249
Look, don't let him come in
and hang about for me.

829
00:53:34,250 --> 00:53:35,457
OK?

830
00:53:36,083 --> 00:53:37,541
Yeah, yeah.

831
00:53:49,625 --> 00:53:50,999
Oh, thanks.

832
00:53:59,333 --> 00:54:01,957
Well, last night ashore then?

833
00:54:02,292 --> 00:54:03,624
Going on the razzle?

834
00:54:04,125 --> 00:54:07,124
Don't go on razzles, Dad.
Just a few pints with me mates.

835
00:54:08,083 --> 00:54:10,082
Navy suits you pretty well,
doesn't it?

836
00:54:10,458 --> 00:54:12,291
- Money's good.
- I don't mean that.

837
00:54:12,792 --> 00:54:13,957
What then?

838
00:54:14,458 --> 00:54:18,457
Well, coming and going, travel.

839
00:54:19,833 --> 00:54:21,332
How long you going this time?

840
00:54:21,958 --> 00:54:23,124
Six months.

841
00:54:24,000 --> 00:54:25,541
A lot of lads don't like that.

842
00:54:26,542 --> 00:54:29,416
Always trying to get exchange posting,
stay ashore.

843
00:54:31,708 --> 00:54:33,666
I don't miss anything when I'm away.

844
00:54:35,583 --> 00:54:37,041
People might miss you.

845
00:54:37,625 --> 00:54:38,582
No.

846
00:54:38,667 --> 00:54:40,707
- Your mum misses you.
- No.

847
00:54:41,625 --> 00:54:43,124
So do I, Vinny.

848
00:54:43,292 --> 00:54:45,082
Look, I don't want to talk about this.

849
00:54:54,500 --> 00:54:55,999
You don't look after yourself.

850
00:54:56,583 --> 00:54:58,082
I get by, thank you.

851
00:54:58,958 --> 00:55:01,582
Time you bought some new clothes,
smarten yourself up a bit.

852
00:55:03,250 --> 00:55:05,124
I don't have the money you've got.

853
00:55:05,708 --> 00:55:07,832
Try keeping out the boozer for a week.

854
00:55:08,458 --> 00:55:10,082
Leave me alone, Vin.

855
00:55:10,875 --> 00:55:12,791
I can say the same for you and all.

856
00:55:18,625 --> 00:55:20,791
Why'd you come anyway?
What you here for?

857
00:55:21,417 --> 00:55:22,541
You're my son.

858
00:55:23,958 --> 00:55:26,041
You don't fucking know
why you come around here

859
00:55:26,125 --> 00:55:28,041
sit about and make me miserable.

860
00:55:29,000 --> 00:55:31,666
Half an hour ago, I was having
a couple of pints with me mates

861
00:55:31,750 --> 00:55:33,166
and I was up, you know?

862
00:55:34,042 --> 00:55:37,999
And now with you in this
pissing awful room, I’m down.

863
00:55:42,042 --> 00:55:43,416
Sod you.

864
00:55:44,833 --> 00:55:46,291
(DOOR OPENS)

865
00:55:47,833 --> 00:55:48,957
(DOOR SLAMS)

866
00:55:58,708 --> 00:56:00,749
(GULLS SQUAWK)

867
00:56:27,333 --> 00:56:28,791
Sailing tomorrow?

868
00:56:30,417 --> 00:56:31,666
That's right, yeah.

869
00:56:33,583 --> 00:56:36,999
What would old Plymouth do
without Jack Tar, eh?

870
00:56:37,417 --> 00:56:39,291
Certainly be a bit quieter, I'd say.

871
00:56:39,833 --> 00:56:42,082
Plymouth does well out of the Navy.

872
00:56:43,292 --> 00:56:44,791
Lived here for years.

873
00:56:45,333 --> 00:56:47,041
Worked in the dockyards.

874
00:56:48,042 --> 00:56:49,666
I've seen it grow.

875
00:56:51,292 --> 00:56:55,041
Yes... Plymouth does well
out of the Navy.

876
00:56:56,042 --> 00:56:57,749
Did well out of the war too.

877
00:56:58,125 --> 00:56:59,582
Bombed flat, wasn't it?

878
00:57:00,417 --> 00:57:02,291
Bombs don't destroy money.

879
00:57:05,583 --> 00:57:07,207
Good life, in the Navy.

880
00:57:09,125 --> 00:57:10,832
I had a lad in the Navy.

881
00:57:11,417 --> 00:57:12,582
Good life.

882
00:57:12,833 --> 00:57:14,541
Sailed all over the world.

883
00:57:17,250 --> 00:57:19,082
Got in a few scrapes, mind.

884
00:57:20,750 --> 00:57:22,499
Goodness me.
(HE CHUCKLES)

885
00:57:24,125 --> 00:57:26,582
Had a wife in every port,
I don't doubt.

886
00:57:30,792 --> 00:57:33,374
(DOG PANTS)

887
00:57:34,000 --> 00:57:35,249
He won't hurt you.

888
00:57:35,625 --> 00:57:37,332
No, I know. I know.

889
00:57:38,500 --> 00:57:39,707
Know about dogs.

890
00:57:40,625 --> 00:57:41,832
Was brought up with 'em.

891
00:57:42,292 --> 00:57:43,749
He needs feeding.

892
00:57:49,125 --> 00:57:50,416
(CHATTER ON TV)

893
00:57:50,500 --> 00:57:53,166
...the opening minute of the second half,
to take the score

894
00:57:53,250 --> 00:57:55,499
to 1 3 points to nil for Australia.

895
00:57:56,167 --> 00:57:58,041
Paul McLean coming into the line...

896
00:57:58,208 --> 00:57:59,374
(TV SWITCHES OFF)

897
00:57:59,500 --> 00:58:00,541
OK then?

898
00:58:00,833 --> 00:58:01,916
Yeah.

899
00:58:02,833 --> 00:58:04,791
Going into town for a pint.

900
00:58:06,792 --> 00:58:08,041
You're starting early.

901
00:58:08,750 --> 00:58:10,541
Oh, I said I'd see Steve.

902
00:58:10,625 --> 00:58:11,749
So?

903
00:58:13,583 --> 00:58:14,791
What's the matter?

904
00:58:16,708 --> 00:58:18,041
(SHE SIGHS)

905
00:58:20,292 --> 00:58:22,541
Can't wait to go, can you?

906
00:58:22,833 --> 00:58:23,832
Eh?

907
00:58:24,250 --> 00:58:25,916
All mates together.

908
00:58:28,250 --> 00:58:29,999
I'll see you at the restaurant then.

909
00:58:30,083 --> 00:58:31,832
You and Sue, me and Steve.

910
00:58:32,083 --> 00:58:33,374
That'll be good, eh?

911
00:58:37,333 --> 00:58:39,666
Doing right by the womenfolk.

912
00:58:41,167 --> 00:58:44,916
MAN:
But God does not need to look into my eyes

913
00:58:45,000 --> 00:58:48,499
to see what wickedness I harbour there!

914
00:58:48,708 --> 00:58:50,499
No, he does not!

915
00:58:50,583 --> 00:58:53,166
For God is not mocked!

916
00:58:54,792 --> 00:58:56,124
Yes!

917
00:58:56,250 --> 00:58:59,041
I can hurry on my way!

918
00:59:02,625 --> 00:59:04,291
(PHONE DIALS)

919
00:59:09,083 --> 00:59:11,916
- VINCENT ON PHONE: Hello, Mum?
- Hello, Vinny.

920
00:59:12,792 --> 00:59:14,332
Where are you talking from?

921
00:59:14,750 --> 00:59:15,957
Are you on your own?

922
00:59:16,292 --> 00:59:18,332
MARIE:
Well, I'm with Stan, of course.

923
00:59:18,417 --> 00:59:19,999
I don't want him to hear us.

924
00:59:20,125 --> 00:59:21,666
Oh, really?

925
00:59:21,792 --> 00:59:23,082
It's private.

926
00:59:24,458 --> 00:59:26,749
Alright, Stan's left the room now.

927
00:59:26,833 --> 00:59:27,749
Good.

928
00:59:27,917 --> 00:59:31,332
Stan and I have been together
for two years, you know?

929
00:59:32,208 --> 00:59:34,499
How much longer are you going to be
so unpleasant about it all?

930
00:59:37,417 --> 00:59:38,582
Vinny?

931
00:59:38,875 --> 00:59:41,207
I don't want to talk about Stan.

932
00:59:41,292 --> 00:59:43,457
Then what do you want to talk about?

933
00:59:45,875 --> 00:59:47,207
Dad come 'round today.

934
00:59:47,583 --> 00:59:50,207
(SHE CHUCKLES)
Well, that explains your bad temper.

935
00:59:50,583 --> 00:59:53,082
Look, he knows when I’m here.
He knows when I'm ashore.

936
00:59:53,167 --> 00:59:54,416
Vinny, what's the matter, love?

937
00:59:54,500 --> 00:59:56,166
He'd know if I didn't
ever write to him again.

938
00:59:56,250 --> 00:59:58,082
He'd look it up in the paper,
see where my ship docked

939
00:59:58,167 --> 01:00:00,541
find out which ship I...
he'd phone the fucking Admiral of the fleet.

940
01:00:00,708 --> 01:00:02,749
Vinny, please.

941
01:00:05,458 --> 01:00:06,582
Hello?

942
01:00:07,542 --> 01:00:09,124
I'm sailing tomorrow morning.

943
01:00:09,458 --> 01:00:12,041
If only you'd contacted me a week ago.

944
01:00:12,125 --> 01:00:14,166
Why the hell haven't you contacted me?

945
01:00:21,333 --> 01:00:22,416
Mum?

946
01:00:22,500 --> 01:00:23,499
What?

947
01:00:23,583 --> 01:00:25,499
Come into town.
We could have a meal or something.

948
01:00:25,583 --> 01:00:27,082
There's a problem.

949
01:00:27,250 --> 01:00:28,749
Well, you can do that, can't you?

950
01:00:28,833 --> 01:00:30,541
No. I can't. I...

951
01:00:30,917 --> 01:00:33,374
Bloody hell, he can do without you
for one evening, can't he?

952
01:00:33,500 --> 01:00:35,749
Explanations always sound so...

953
01:00:37,333 --> 01:00:41,249
Look, there's been some trouble
down at Stan's disco, I...

954
01:00:42,083 --> 01:00:44,082
I don't want him
down there tonight.

955
01:00:45,000 --> 01:00:46,749
Especially tonight.

956
01:00:47,542 --> 01:00:48,874
It'd be dangerous.

957
01:00:48,958 --> 01:00:50,582
Oh, what is all this?

958
01:00:50,667 --> 01:00:53,332
If I let him out of my sight,
he'll be down there.

959
01:00:53,667 --> 01:00:56,874
Oh, my God, Vinny, you're so unkind.

960
01:00:56,958 --> 01:00:59,916
Always, always, you make
these impossible suggestions

961
01:01:00,000 --> 01:01:03,166
then when I can't make it work,
you go off in a bloody rage

962
01:01:03,250 --> 01:01:05,332
and then of course it's all my fault.

963
01:01:06,417 --> 01:01:08,916
I... want to see you.

964
01:01:09,958 --> 01:01:10,916
I do.

965
01:01:11,208 --> 01:01:12,416
Yeah, yeah.

966
01:01:13,000 --> 01:01:15,249
Vinny, I'm just too frightened.

967
01:01:15,375 --> 01:01:16,541
Don't you see?

968
01:01:17,833 --> 01:01:22,791
Stan is for every day,
not just for once or twice a year.

969
01:01:24,333 --> 01:01:25,457
You...

970
01:01:26,708 --> 01:01:28,499
Vinny, do you know what I'm saying?

971
01:01:28,583 --> 01:01:29,624
Yeah.

972
01:01:30,458 --> 01:01:31,666
Fuck off.

973
01:01:31,750 --> 01:01:33,291
(HANDSET CLATTERS)

974
01:01:41,375 --> 01:01:43,166
Where have you been?

975
01:01:43,250 --> 01:01:44,707
Was out walking.

976
01:01:46,333 --> 01:01:48,291
- You been awake long?
- Yes.

977
01:01:52,667 --> 01:01:53,666
It was a long walk.

978
01:01:54,417 --> 01:01:55,541
Doesn't matter, does it?

979
01:01:55,917 --> 01:01:58,166
Well, I'm glad you finally
remembered me.

980
01:01:58,792 --> 01:01:59,916
What's the matter?

981
01:02:00,458 --> 01:02:04,041
It's not much fun, that's all.
Waking up here, all by myself.

982
01:02:04,750 --> 01:02:06,332
I'm sorry, OK?

983
01:02:12,042 --> 01:02:13,416
Where are we gonna eat?

984
01:02:13,500 --> 01:02:15,124
Oh, I booked a table at the Ganges.

985
01:02:15,208 --> 01:02:17,957
- You know, the Indian, where we...
- Where we ate last time.

986
01:02:18,875 --> 01:02:20,624
It was good, wasn't it?

987
01:02:21,792 --> 01:02:23,124
Bloody hell.

988
01:02:25,208 --> 01:02:27,457
Oh, I meant to hang this up.

989
01:02:27,625 --> 01:02:28,749
Bugger.

990
01:02:34,833 --> 01:02:37,249
(HAIRDRYER WHIRS)

991
01:02:56,333 --> 01:02:58,666
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

992
01:03:07,208 --> 01:03:08,999
TV PRESENTER:
Tonight we are pleased to welcome

993
01:03:09,083 --> 01:03:12,624
one of the senior officers
from HMS Impregnable

994
01:03:12,708 --> 01:03:15,166
Commander Phillip Masterson RN.

995
01:03:15,333 --> 01:03:17,166
He's talking in our studio.

996
01:03:18,958 --> 01:03:20,874
MASTERSON:
Ah, yes, I think we shall have

997
01:03:20,958 --> 01:03:22,916
a fairly active social life.

998
01:03:23,125 --> 01:03:24,916
Good, eh? Tokyo.

999
01:03:25,542 --> 01:03:26,666
Great.

1000
01:03:27,833 --> 01:03:31,082
PRESENTER: Have you had much
in the way of female company?

1001
01:03:31,167 --> 01:03:35,124
Oh gosh, yes. The ladies fly out
to join us in Los Angeles

1002
01:03:35,250 --> 01:03:36,374
to keep an eye on us.

1003
01:03:36,458 --> 01:03:39,332
That must make a long tour
that much better, I'm sure.

1004
01:03:39,417 --> 01:03:40,582
Seriously, yes it does.

1005
01:03:40,667 --> 01:03:42,957
Frankly, the Navy has moved
a long way on these matters.

1006
01:03:43,292 --> 01:03:46,207
I mean, let us not forget
that the Navy is recruiting

1007
01:03:46,292 --> 01:03:49,207
in competition with industry
for the best brains

1008
01:03:49,292 --> 01:03:52,082
and chaps with top management ability.

1009
01:03:52,167 --> 01:03:57,082
We really have to look to our laurels
in matters of welfare

1010
01:03:57,167 --> 01:03:58,582
conditions of work, and so on.

1011
01:03:58,833 --> 01:04:01,666
PRESENTER: Commander, how many men
are there on Impregnable?

1012
01:04:01,750 --> 01:04:03,582
MASTERSON:
About 500.

1013
01:04:03,667 --> 01:04:04,999
Ready, Mark, old son?

1014
01:04:05,083 --> 01:04:05,999
Yeah.

1015
01:04:06,083 --> 01:04:09,541
We heard you were legless last night,
you naughty boy.

1016
01:04:09,750 --> 01:04:10,999
Jumping the gun.

1017
01:04:11,083 --> 01:04:12,207
Let's go.

1018
01:04:12,625 --> 01:04:14,582
MASTERSON:
It's a lot of people in a confined space.

1019
01:04:14,750 --> 01:04:18,124
We jolly well have to learn
to rub along together.

1020
01:04:18,333 --> 01:04:21,916
And we do, you know,
most of the time.

1021
01:04:56,625 --> 01:04:58,749
(MACHINES BEEP)

1022
01:05:01,542 --> 01:05:04,207
(NOISY CHATTER AND LAUGHTER)

1023
01:05:29,292 --> 01:05:30,707
(CAR HORN HONKS)

1024
01:05:53,417 --> 01:05:56,791
(MUSIC: "ARMED AND READY"
BY MICHAEL SCHENKER GROUP)

1025
01:06:10,375 --> 01:06:11,916
A pint of lager please.

1026
01:06:12,167 --> 01:06:13,624
A pint of bitter, please.

1027
01:06:14,292 --> 01:06:16,416
♪ Are you feeling right? ♪

1028
01:06:17,167 --> 01:06:21,249
♪ Cos I need you now
like I never did before ♪

1029
01:06:22,958 --> 01:06:24,999
♪ Is it hard enough? ♪

1030
01:06:25,708 --> 01:06:27,999
♪ Is it long enough? ♪

1031
01:06:28,083 --> 01:06:29,624
CHRIS:
We're not staying here long.

1032
01:06:29,708 --> 01:06:32,041
MALCOLM:
It's a laugh, here, bikers' pub.

1033
01:06:32,917 --> 01:06:35,499
Here, you know that bloke
who got done over

1034
01:06:35,583 --> 01:06:36,999
at Dol's last night?

1035
01:06:37,083 --> 01:06:39,207
- Yeah, he's from Raleigh, weren't he?
- No, he weren't.

1036
01:06:39,292 --> 01:06:40,457
He ain't Navy.

1037
01:06:41,125 --> 01:06:43,207
They told me at the hospital.

1038
01:06:43,333 --> 01:06:45,166
Been up there with flowers then?

1039
01:06:45,417 --> 01:06:46,499
